WEBVTT

00:06.762 --> 00:08.680
Sorry, but giving up
is not my "fort."

00:08.682 --> 00:09.931
You mean "for-tay""

00:09.933 --> 00:11.883
No, I mean "fort,"
it's pronounced "fort."

00:11.885 --> 00:13.267
How much you want to bet?

00:13.269 --> 00:16.303
Oh, well, I'll bet you the
house, but you know what?

00:16.305 --> 00:17.471
Let's start with 20 bucks.

00:17.473 --> 00:18.573
I'll go easy on you.

00:18.575 --> 00:19.557
Done.

00:19.559 --> 00:21.242
Let's see.

00:21.244 --> 00:22.777
It begins with an "F."

00:22.779 --> 00:24.829
Yes, I'm aware of that.

00:24.831 --> 00:27.248
Forte-- pronounced "fort,"
not "for-tay."

00:27.250 --> 00:28.499
Read it and weep.

00:28.501 --> 00:29.500
Can't be.

00:29.502 --> 00:31.586
Oh, but it so can be.

00:33.172 --> 00:35.123
Mm-hmm, come on.
(groans)

00:35.125 --> 00:36.874
Hey, Strunk and White, you done?

00:36.876 --> 00:38.509
Yeah, we're done, Sarge.

00:38.511 --> 00:39.510
Thank you.

00:39.512 --> 00:41.129
You asked me last week
for a heads up

00:41.131 --> 00:43.831
next time we got
a bad traffic accident, right?

00:43.833 --> 00:45.383
Yeah, why?
Well, we just got

00:45.385 --> 00:47.385
two cars go through
the guardrail,

00:47.387 --> 00:49.437
over the edge of the BQE.

00:49.439 --> 00:50.555
Two cars.

00:50.557 --> 00:51.606
Okay, you know what?

00:51.608 --> 00:52.807
Uh, we'll check it out.

00:52.809 --> 00:55.176
Since when do detectives
catch car accidents?

00:55.178 --> 00:56.894
When they don't think
they're accidents.

00:56.896 --> 00:58.363
Come on.

01:01.367 --> 01:03.401
(helicopter blades whirring)

01:03.403 --> 01:05.570
(siren wailing)

01:11.526 --> 01:13.711
(overlapping shouting)

01:21.920 --> 01:23.638
Detective Reagan.
This is Detective Lansing.

01:23.640 --> 01:24.689
What can you tell us?

01:24.691 --> 01:26.057
What you see is
what you get.

01:27.760 --> 01:30.178
The woman driving the SUV
fell asleep at the wheel,

01:30.180 --> 01:31.979
wound up driving herself
and this poor bastard

01:31.981 --> 01:32.930
over the edge.

01:32.932 --> 01:34.015
Both DOA?

01:34.017 --> 01:34.982
That's right.

01:34.984 --> 01:36.017
This falling asleep
at the wheel--

01:36.019 --> 01:37.018
where'd you get that from?

01:37.020 --> 01:38.169
That's what
two eyewitnesses say.

01:38.171 --> 01:39.504
Where are the eyewitnesses?

01:39.506 --> 01:40.772
They had to go to work,
you know.

01:40.774 --> 01:41.856
We took their statements.

01:41.858 --> 01:42.890
You let
the eyewitnesses leave?

01:42.892 --> 01:44.391
You know, <i>Psychology</i>
<i>Today</i> says

01:44.393 --> 01:47.328
eyewitness testimony isn't
as reliable as we thought.

01:47.330 --> 01:48.446
Psychology Today?

01:48.448 --> 01:49.447
You don't read it?

01:49.449 --> 01:51.032
You do?
I do.

01:51.034 --> 01:52.366
Look, I don't read
much of anything,

01:52.368 --> 01:53.918
but I agree with
her on this.

01:53.920 --> 01:55.503
I don't have much faith
in the testimony

01:55.505 --> 01:57.755
of someone driving 50 miles
an hour and late for work.

01:57.757 --> 01:59.573
Is there something going on
here, detectives?

01:59.575 --> 02:01.342
Just show us where
the other victim is.

02:01.344 --> 02:02.543
The woman
driving the SUV?

02:02.545 --> 02:03.961
Right this way.

02:06.098 --> 02:09.750
If you don't mind me asking, why
are two Major Case detectives

02:09.752 --> 02:11.519
at the scene of a car accident?

02:11.521 --> 02:13.420
We're crossing our fingers.

02:13.422 --> 02:14.388
Detectives?

02:14.390 --> 02:15.807
She the only
one in the car?

02:15.809 --> 02:16.757
That's right.

02:16.759 --> 02:18.693
Detective.
Can you open it up?

02:18.695 --> 02:20.728
(unzips)

02:24.766 --> 02:26.100
What's the
cause of death?

02:26.102 --> 02:27.318
That's a 50-foot drop.

02:27.320 --> 02:29.537
Yeah, I saw that.

02:36.712 --> 02:38.246
And that,

02:38.248 --> 02:41.632
that's where a .223 round
went through her skull.

02:41.634 --> 02:43.050
That's the cause of death.

02:46.889 --> 02:49.090
(elevator bell dings)

02:52.794 --> 02:54.979
Thanks, Abby.

02:58.400 --> 03:00.434
Beef up patrols
on all major highways?

03:00.436 --> 03:02.687
Put Highway Patrol
on 12-hour tours.

03:02.689 --> 03:03.971
Yes, sir.

03:03.973 --> 03:05.356
All right, people,
let's take it

03:05.358 --> 03:06.357
from the top.

03:06.359 --> 03:07.942
You know what
I'm about to say.

03:07.944 --> 03:09.911
I do.

03:09.913 --> 03:11.478
And you already
disagree with me.

03:11.480 --> 03:13.698
I enjoy watching
you make your case.

03:13.700 --> 03:15.750
We now have two people who have
been shot on our highways,

03:15.752 --> 03:18.619
Frank, a week apart
but from the same gun.

03:18.621 --> 03:20.671
Tell me something I don't know.
We need to hold a press conference.

03:20.673 --> 03:24.425
This is a serial sniper,
a highway hit man.

03:24.427 --> 03:26.544
Oh, you're already writing copy.

03:26.546 --> 03:27.678
I know what
you're going to say.

03:27.680 --> 03:29.146
If we go public, we're gonna
set off a panic.

03:29.148 --> 03:30.848
We could.
Frankly,

03:30.850 --> 03:32.884
I think a little panic
here is a good thing.

03:32.886 --> 03:34.302
Given the circumstances,

03:34.304 --> 03:36.103
why not have everyone on alert?

03:37.306 --> 03:38.556
Thin?

03:38.558 --> 03:40.174
Just a little.

03:40.176 --> 03:43.027
Frank, I may not be doing a very
good job articulating why,

03:43.029 --> 03:46.364
but I know in my bones we have
to tell the public about this.

03:46.366 --> 03:50.401
Because sometimes it's the 12th
man that wins the game for you.

03:50.403 --> 03:51.685
What?

03:51.687 --> 03:53.154
There are eight million people
in this city.

03:53.156 --> 03:56.741
That's 16 million eyeballs
out there looking for clues

03:56.743 --> 03:59.160
that can help us catch
this son of a bitch.

03:59.162 --> 04:01.229
You were going to hold
a press conference all along,

04:01.231 --> 04:02.213
weren't you?

04:02.215 --> 04:04.582
Shall we?

04:07.085 --> 04:10.504
SEAN:
May 24, 1883.

04:10.506 --> 04:11.589
That's exactly right.

04:11.591 --> 04:13.224
Which makes the
bridge how old?

04:13.226 --> 04:14.175
Um...

04:14.177 --> 04:16.644
NICKY:
129.

04:16.646 --> 04:19.981
That's right, so imagine that,
just think about it.

04:19.983 --> 04:22.850
In an age before computers
and heavy machinery,

04:22.852 --> 04:24.885
the men and women
of this city

04:24.887 --> 04:26.687
built the greatest
bridge ever

04:26.689 --> 04:29.357
with just their bare
hands and their hearts

04:29.359 --> 04:30.825
and minds.

04:30.827 --> 04:31.826
JACK:
That's cool,

04:31.828 --> 04:32.910
but why do
we need to know

04:32.912 --> 04:34.445
so much
about the Brooklyn Bridge?

04:34.447 --> 04:37.415
Because your great-great-
grandfather helped build it.

04:37.417 --> 04:38.399
He did?

04:38.401 --> 04:39.566
ERIN:
That's right,

04:39.568 --> 04:41.369
that's my mother's
dad's dad.

04:41.371 --> 04:42.620
Wow.
He was the first one

04:42.622 --> 04:44.755
of our family
to come to America.

04:44.757 --> 04:46.924
Yep, and when he laid
those limestone blocks

04:46.926 --> 04:49.260
down, he laid

04:49.262 --> 04:50.711
our roots with it.

04:50.713 --> 04:52.096
Our family has lasted
here in Brooklyn

04:52.098 --> 04:54.081
for as long
as that Great Bridge has.

04:54.083 --> 04:55.582
JACK: Wow.
That's cool, right?

04:55.584 --> 04:57.018
Yeah.

04:57.020 --> 04:58.352
Let's go.

05:04.092 --> 05:05.559
Whoa. Hey, watch it!
Watch it!

05:07.379 --> 05:08.362
Sean!

05:10.515 --> 05:13.284
Sean!

05:13.286 --> 05:14.402
MAN:
Oh, my gosh.

05:14.404 --> 05:15.353
Oh, my God.

05:15.355 --> 05:16.621
Sean, are you okay?

05:17.873 --> 05:20.408
Sean.
MAN: You need any help?

05:20.410 --> 05:21.742
WOMAN:
Run, get some help.

05:23.662 --> 05:25.997
Nicky, call 911.

05:28.216 --> 05:30.418
Oh, my gosh, Sean.

05:33.825 --> 05:37.825
<font color=#00FF00>♪ Blue Bloods 3x10 ♪</font>
<font color=#00FFFF>Fathers and Sons</font>
